{"amendments":[{"body":"Tighten `FsTaskRunLineageStore::update_task_run` so a completion with `run_id` only finalizes an exact matching attempt. Today `src/adapters/fs.rs:2894-2928` falls back to the lone unfinished runless row when no exact `run_id` match exists, and `record_bead_completion` no longer supplies `started_at` to disambiguate (`src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:457-492`). That means a completion for a brand-new named retry can be written onto an older open attempt instead of failing fast, which corrupts the bead audit trail.","rationale":"This is a correctness issue: the persisted lineage can attribute the outcome of one retry to a different attempt."},{"body":"Handle stale legacy/open attempts when starting a new named retry. In `src/adapters/fs.rs:2827-2836`, superseding only happens when the new start is itself runless; if a new explicit `run_id` starts after an older runless row, the old row is left permanently `running`. `find_runs_for_bead` then returns contradictory history for the same bead (`src/adapters/fs.rs:3111-3127`), e.g. one attempt still `running` even after a later retry already `succeeded`. Either mark the older row as superseded at start time or reject the new start until the old row is resolved.","rationale":"This breaks the goal of answering “what happened to bead X?” from milestone state alone, because the query can report both a finished retry and a forever-running prior attempt."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone lineage/model/service/fs changes and their tests. I found two correctness gaps in legacy/open-attempt handling: named completions can be attached to the wrong historical row, and named retries can leave stale attempts permanently marked as running."}